1519–":"10 november 1519–Overleden","1519–Male":"1519–Overleden","1550–1580":"1550–1580","–Male":"Overleden","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","10 November 1519":"10 november 1519","14 November 1519":"14 november 1519","1550":"1550","1580":"1580","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","Altham, Lancashire, England":"Altham, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"10 November 1519–":"10 November 1519–Deceased","1519–Male":"1519–Deceased","1550–1580":"1550–1580","–Male":"Deceased","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","10 November 1519":"10 November 1519","14 November 1519":"14 November 1519","1550":"1550","1580":"1580","1519":"1519","1549":"1549","Altham, Lancashire, England":"Altham, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jackson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and northern Irish: patronymic from   Jack  . In North America, this surname has absorbed other patronymics beginning with <i>J-</i> in various European languages, in particular those derived from equivalents or short forms and other derivatives of the personal name   Jacob  , e.g. Norwegian   Jacobsen   or   Jakobsen   and, in some cases, Slovenian <b>Jakše</b> (from a derivative of the personal name   Jakob  ). This surname is also very common among African Americans (see also 2 below).","African American: from the personal name <i>Jackson</i> (or <i>Andrew Jackson</i>), adopted in honor of Andrew Jackson, the 7th president of the US; or adoption of the surname in 1 above, in many cases probably for the same reason.","History: This extremely common British name was brought over by numerous different bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. One forebear was the father and namesake of the seventh US president, Andrew Jackson, who migrated to SC from Carrickfergus in the north of Ireland in 1765. The Confederate General Thomas ‘Stonewall’ Jackson came from VA, where his great-grandfather John, likewise of Scotch–Irish stock, had settled after emigrating to America in 1748."],"variants":[{"name":"Jack","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Jak</i>, <i>Jakke</i>, <i>Jagge</i>, <i>Jake</i>, <i>Jeke</i>, <i>Jegge</i>, a Picard-Flemish denasalized form of Old Picard and Middle Dutch <i>Janke</i>, a pet form of <i>Jan</i> (see   John  ). It was introduced by Flemings and Picards into Norman and Anglo-Norman usage, whence it became a common English and Scottish pet form of <i>John</i>. Although the surname is mainly Scottish in distribution, it also occurs in England, though the more common form there is   Jackson  .","English: occasionally perhaps from a Middle English borrowing of the Old French personal name <i>Jacque(s)</i> (James). However, it is uncertain whether English <i>Jack</i> was ever used as an alternative to <i>James</i>.","Native American (e.g. Navajo): adoption of the English personal name <i>Jack</i> (see 1 above) as a surname."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":29,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":38,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of 